<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-253-703  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 253 703.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Jan 9 1989 v6 n1 p73(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ross takes aim at banking, thrift software markets. (Ross Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ballou, Melinda-Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Ross Systems markets accounting software in the thrift andmortgage banking industries.andP;  Another company, Saddlebrook ofCambridge, MA, works with Ross Systems.andP;  Saddlebrook is the majorsupplier of DEC-based systems in the thrift and mortgage bankingindustries.andP;  Special terminals are developed for the thriftmarket.andP;  Around 17 percent of the thrift industry software marketis held by DEC. In accordance with the licensing agreement,Saddlebrook has exclusive right to sell and support the RossRenaissance series accounting line.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ross Systems Inc. (marketing).andO;Topic:     Market ShareMarket PenetrationSales EngineersFinancial SoftwareBankingMortgage.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Ross Takes Aim At Banking, Thrift Software MarketsandM;PALO ALTO, Calif.andP;  -- Accounting software vendor Ross Systems is targetingthe thrift and mortgage banking industries with the help of a hiredgun--Saddlebrook of Cambridge, Mass., the leading supplier of DEC-basedsystems in that marketplace--according to company officials.andM;&quot;There are specialized terminals for the thrift market, and there'stremendous interest in this area at DEC.andP;  But the question is: Where are theapplications?&quot; said Dennis Vohs, chief executive officer at Ross, based here.andM;&quot;While IBM has been a dominant force in banking, in the savings and loan[industry] it has been a mix [of vendors].andP;  It's a good marketplace for DEC,and there's been a major emphasis on providing strategic applications withcompanies like Saddlebrook,&quot; he said.andM;Vohs added that DEC itself holds approximately 17 percent of the softwaremarket in the thrift area of the banking industry.andM;As a result of this new Ross-Saddlebrook licensing aggreement, Saddlebrookhas exclusive rights to sell and support Ross' Renaissance series accountingproducts.andP;  The company will develop and offer banking-specific enhancementsto FinancialPlus, Ross' accounting software for the Renaissance series.andM;Saddlebrook's own accounting software is available only on PDP-11s, althoughthe company last year upgraded its Advanced System and System M on-linetransaction processing (OLTP) and lending-management software to the VAX withgreat success, company officials said.andM;&quot;It's a perfect product for our marketplace,&quot; said Ken Elmer, Saddlebrook'smanager of systems engineering, about Ross' FinancialPlus.andP;  &quot;We had theoption of doing our own conversion of our accounting software or of going outto look for an outside product, and Ross met our needs.&quot;andM;The agreement is part of a Ross strategy to establish relationships with DECapplication vendors that are established in a variety of markets.andM;&quot;We're looking for partners in the various specialty markets where thepartners have a good, strong market share,&quot; Ross' Vohs said.andM;Vohs said Saddlebrook brought out a new line of software based onobject-oriented technology that was designed to make use of DEC transactionprocessing.andM;Richard Streller, CEO at Saddlebrook, said OLTP performance and machinecapacity were important considerations for Saddlebrook when it decided tostay with DEC, but he declined to indicate whether the introduction of theVAX 6200 was a key factor.andO;</TEXT></DOC>